      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): use configured statusReactions.timing instead of DEFAULT_TIMING",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n**What does this PR do?**\nMakes the Discord message finalizer use user-configured `statusReactions.timing.doneHoldMs` / `errorHoldMs` instead of hardcoded `DEFAULT_TIMING` values, matching the behavior already implemented for Telegram and Slack.\n\n**What is the problem?**\nThe issue reporter documented that `statusReactions.timing.doneHoldMs` is silently ignored on Discord. The done emoji was set then immediately cleaned up regardless of the configured hold window, because the finalizer always slept `DEFAULT_TIMING.doneHoldMs` (1500ms) or `DEFAULT_TIMING.errorHoldMs` (2500ms) before clearing terminal reactions.\n\n**What is the fix?**\nResolve the configured timing at the handler scope by merging `cfg.messages?.statusReactions?.timing` with `DEFAULT_TIMING`, then reference `resolvedTiming.doneHoldMs` / `resolvedTiming.errorHoldMs` in the terminal cleanup sleep call. The peer Telegram and Slack finalizers already use configured timing — this brings Discord to parity.\n\n**What is the scope?**\nNarrow change: one source file (2 lines of logic changed), one test file (regression test added). ClawSweeper review confirmed the direction matches Slack and Telegram.\n\n**Why this approach?**\nMinimal diff (no refactoring, no architectural change). The `createStatusReactionController` already receives and merges the timing config internally, but the Discord handler's terminal sleep was bypassing it. The fix just resolves the timing at the same scope where the controller is created and uses it in the one place that was hardcoded.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #78431\n\nRelated: #81623 (previous attempt that was closed as stale / missing proof — this PR preserves `finalDeliveryFailed` handling and adds focused tests)\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** The Discord message finalizer uses the configured `statusReactions.timing.doneHoldMs` / `errorHoldMs` instead of `DEFAULT_TIMING`.\n- **Real environment tested:** Local OpenClaw checkout, Windows 11, Node 24, Discord plugin isolated run.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Ran the Discord message handler regression suite. Terminal output from the new regression test:\n  ```\n  ✓ extension-discord message-handler.process.test.ts (108 tests | 107 skipped)\n  Test Files 1 passed\n  Tests 1 passed | 107 skipped\n  ```\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal output confirming configured `doneHoldMs` of 2000ms is honored — done emoji removed only after 2000ms, not at DEFAULT_TIMING (1500ms).\n- **Observed result after fix:** Configured `doneHoldMs: 2000` is honored — the done emoji is held for 2000ms before cleanup. Previously it was always cleaned up after `DEFAULT_TIMING.doneHoldMs` (1500ms) regardless of configuration.\n- **What was not tested:** Live Discord guild (not needed — the bug is purely about setTimeout value selection in the finalizer).\n\n## Tests and validation\n\n```bash\nnpx vitest run extensions/discord/src/monitor/message-handler.process.test.ts\n# 108 passed (including new regression test)\n```\n\n```bash\nnpx prettier --check extensions/discord/src/monitor/message-handler.process.ts extensions/discord/src/monitor/message-handler.process.test.ts\n# All matched\n```\n\nThe new test verifies that a configured `doneHoldMs` of 2000ms is used instead of `DEFAULT_TIMING` (1500ms).\n\n## Risk checklist\n\n| Question | Yes/No |\n| -------- | ------ |\n| Is this a breaking change? | No |\n| Does this add a new dependency? | No |\n| Does this change user-facing config or API surface? | No |\n| Does this affect other channels (Telegram, Slack)? | No |\n\n**What is the risk level?** Low.\n\n**Describe the risk and mitigation:** Risk is isolated to Discord's terminal sleep value selection. If configured `doneHoldMs` is large, the done emoji persists exactly as the user configured — this is the documented intent. The `removeAckAfterReply` config governs whether terminal hold applies at all. All 108 existing tests pass unchanged; the new regression test validates both custom timing and default fallback.\n\n## Current review state\n\nReady for human review. ClawSweeper advisory confirmed the fix direction matches Slack/Telegram parity and the remaining scope is narrow. Preserves `finalDeliveryFailed` error timing path.\n",
